==English==

===Noun===
'''ragamuffin'''
# a [[dirty]], [[shabbily]]-[[clothed]] [[child]]; an [[urchin]]
# ''(According to [[Brewer's Dictionary of Phrase and Fable]]):'' A ''muffin'' is a poor thing of a creature, a 'regular muff'; so that a ''ragamuffin'' is a sorry creature in rags.
#:"I have led my ragamuffins where they are peppered."  [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]]: [[Henry_IV,_part_1|I Henry IV]], v, 3.

===Usage note===
''(Second definition):'' Currently, it is archaic [[slang]], used either for [[anachronism|anachronistic]] effect or as dialogue in [[historical fiction]].